x4freetext: The Back-n white neutron source at
The neutrons were produced by double bunched
proton beam (1.6 GeV, ~20 kW) bombarding a tungsten
target. The neutron flux was about 3.5E6 n/cm2s.
Two enriched (90%) 10B samples were 5.0 cm in
diameter, evaporated on an aluminum foil 50 um in
thickness. Each sample was 82.59 and 85.05 ug/cm2 in
The charged particles were detected by the
Light-charged Particle Detector Array system, which
mainly consisted of a silicon detector array and a
silicon detectors with 500 um in thickness could
cover the emission angle of the particles from 19.2
to 160.8 deg. The distance between the center of the
silicon detector and that of the 10B sample was 20.0
cm. A gridded ionization chamber (GIC) and three
delta E-E detectors were installed and tested.
The neutron energy was determined by TOF
method, the length of the flight path was 57.99 m.
The events were measured in turns, about 16 h for
measurement foreground and about 8 h measurement for
background for each turn. The total beam duration was
were normalized according to standard cross section
